1
00:00:14,056 --> 00:00:16,058
[melancholic classical music
playing]

2
00:01:10,571 --> 00:01:12,573
[sizzling]

3
00:01:16,410 --> 00:01:18,412
[cicadas buzzing]

4
00:01:21,749 --> 00:01:23,208
[birds chirping]

5
00:01:23,209 --> 00:01:24,084
Yeah...

6
00:01:25,085 --> 00:01:26,420
Come on, fall!

7
00:01:29,256 --> 00:01:31,258
[wind rustling]

8
00:01:45,356 --> 00:01:47,524
They must really like you.

9
00:01:47,525 --> 00:01:48,900
Sending you expensive eel.

10
00:01:48,901 --> 00:01:50,777
It's not that they like me.

11
00:01:50,778 --> 00:01:53,154
They're going to work me even harder.

12
00:01:53,155 --> 00:01:54,823
Those Americans too

13
00:01:54,824 --> 00:01:57,743
must know that eels
make men perform better.

14
00:01:58,911 --> 00:02:01,997
They even sent it on your birthday.

15
00:02:03,499 --> 00:02:04,333
[mock groaning]

16
00:02:04,917 --> 00:02:06,043
The kids will hear!

17
00:02:07,044 --> 00:02:10,547
[Man-su] I need eel! Eel!

18
00:02:10,548 --> 00:02:12,841
- Come and eat!
- [playful cello music playing]

19
00:02:12,842 --> 00:02:16,970
Dad sweated in the heat grilling these.

20
00:02:16,971 --> 00:02:18,055
I'll go.

21
00:02:19,557 --> 00:02:21,559
[cello music continues]

22
00:02:24,812 --> 00:02:25,980
A snake?

23
00:02:26,897 --> 00:02:28,481
Snakes don't taste this good!

24
00:02:28,482 --> 00:02:31,651
Dad's company sent it,
for doing a good job.

25
00:02:31,652 --> 00:02:33,070
It's not even a holiday.

26
00:02:33,988 --> 00:02:35,865
[Si-one] Couldn't they give us beef?

27
00:02:36,991 --> 00:02:38,117
Ri-one.

28
00:02:38,701 --> 00:02:39,660
Dinner.

29
00:02:42,454 --> 00:02:45,124
Come on. Let's eat.

30
00:02:46,625 --> 00:02:48,501
Let the cello take a nap.

31
00:02:48,502 --> 00:02:49,961
[classical music playing]

32
00:02:49,962 --> 00:02:51,547
- [chair scraping]
[Miri] Oh.

33
00:02:52,339 --> 00:02:53,257
What's this?

34
00:03:03,267 --> 00:03:06,145
Honey!

35
00:03:08,898 --> 00:03:11,233
Must've been expensive!

36
00:03:12,192 --> 00:03:14,861
Well, I can afford decent dance shoes.

37
00:03:14,862 --> 00:03:17,697
Mmm. Aren't Mom's shoes pretty?

38
00:03:17,698 --> 00:03:18,865
Eat up.

39
00:03:18,866 --> 00:03:19,992
[Miri squealing]

40
00:03:21,577 --> 00:03:23,662
I'll be able to dance so well in these.

41
00:03:26,749 --> 00:03:29,959
They say not to gift shoes to your lover.

42
00:03:29,960 --> 00:03:31,711
- [Si-one] Why?
- [Ri-one] Why?

43
00:03:31,712 --> 00:03:33,755
'Cause they might run away in them.

44
00:03:33,756 --> 00:03:34,881
[Man-su chuckles]

45
00:03:34,882 --> 00:03:37,760
Seems your dad is confident.

46
00:03:39,470 --> 00:03:40,429
Come on.

47
00:03:41,347 --> 00:03:43,432
We need to practice when we can.

48
00:03:45,059 --> 00:03:47,226
Ready, start!

49
00:03:47,227 --> 00:03:48,895
- One two three...
- [barks]

50
00:03:48,896 --> 00:03:53,233
...two, two, three, three, two, three...

51
00:03:54,944 --> 00:03:57,655
- [Miri laughs]
- [Man-su exclaims]

52
00:03:58,322 --> 00:03:59,447
[Miri sighs]

53
00:03:59,448 --> 00:04:01,532
[melancholic
classical music playing]

54
00:04:01,533 --> 00:04:03,117
[Miri humming]

55
00:04:03,118 --> 00:04:04,411
[sniffs]

56
00:04:04,995 --> 00:04:05,829
[grunts]

57
00:04:08,707 --> 00:04:09,708
Mm-mm, mm-mm.

58
00:04:11,961 --> 00:04:13,128
[Miri hums]

59
00:04:15,631 --> 00:04:16,548
[sighs]

60
00:04:18,258 --> 00:04:20,009
THANKS FOR YOUR HARD WORK
AND YEARS OF DEDICATION TO SOLAR PAPER.

61
00:04:20,010 --> 00:04:22,429
[Miri grunts] Damned paper...

62
00:04:23,555 --> 00:04:25,807
- Honey, come here.
- Hm?

63
00:04:25,808 --> 00:04:26,809
Why?

64
00:04:28,602 --> 00:04:30,229
Come on.

65
00:04:30,980 --> 00:04:32,523
Come on, Ri-one.

66
00:04:35,150 --> 00:04:41,198
RI-TWO
SI-TWO

67
00:04:44,994 --> 00:04:46,577
Just three minutes more.

68
00:04:46,578 --> 00:04:47,870
- [Si-one groans]
- [Miri grunts]

69
00:04:47,871 --> 00:04:48,998
One minute.

70
00:04:57,172 --> 00:04:58,882
Know what I'm feeling now?

71
00:05:02,553 --> 00:05:04,221
I've got it all.

72
00:05:04,805 --> 00:05:05,806
[Miri chuckles]

73
00:05:21,363 --> 00:05:23,365
[whirring]

74
00:05:30,789 --> 00:05:32,791
[machinery whirring]

75
00:05:34,918 --> 00:05:36,920
[speaking indistinctly]

76
00:05:40,507 --> 00:05:45,137
[Man-su] You people bought Solar Paper,
where I devoted 25 years of my life.

77
00:05:45,888 --> 00:05:50,059
But as soon as you take over, you say
you'll cut 20% of the production line?

78
00:05:50,684 --> 00:05:53,187
And you ask for a list
of names to fire?

79
00:05:53,896 --> 00:05:56,815
Names of veterans
who taught me their craft?

80
00:05:57,649 --> 00:06:00,360
Names of young men
who came of age in this factory?

81
00:06:01,612 --> 00:06:04,530
Innocent workers who lovingly
cared for these machines,

82
00:06:04,531 --> 00:06:08,285
you want me to point a gun at their heads?

83
00:06:08,994 --> 00:06:10,287
I can't do it.

84
00:06:11,955 --> 00:06:14,207
Guns are meant to be aimed
at one's enemies!

85
00:06:14,208 --> 00:06:15,124
STOP! THINK! ACT!

86
00:06:15,125 --> 00:06:18,294
I cannot give you that list.

87
00:06:18,295 --> 00:06:20,421
[thumping]

88
00:06:20,422 --> 00:06:22,590
[Man-su] You Americans say

89
00:06:22,591 --> 00:06:24,551
to be fired is to be "axed"?

90
00:06:25,177 --> 00:06:27,303
Know what we say in Korea?

91
00:06:27,304 --> 00:06:29,013
Off with your head!

92
00:06:29,014 --> 00:06:30,891
So being fired

93
00:06:31,975 --> 00:06:36,062
is having your head chopped
clear off with an ax!

94
00:06:36,063 --> 00:06:38,065
[engine roaring]

95
00:06:38,857 --> 00:06:40,859
[beeping]

96
00:06:41,401 --> 00:06:42,485
JOB FOR LIFE, OLD SHOES

97
00:06:42,486 --> 00:06:45,446
"If you don't start a union,
we guarantee a job for life."

98
00:06:45,447 --> 00:06:47,490
That beautiful tradition...

99
00:06:47,491 --> 00:06:50,660
- [rumbling]
- ...tossed out like old shoes!

100
00:06:50,661 --> 00:06:52,620
[shouting] To you Americans...!

101
00:06:52,621 --> 00:06:53,872
Damn, my throat...

102
00:06:54,373 --> 00:06:56,624
I said to do this in the warehouse.

103
00:06:56,625 --> 00:06:58,669
All because you wanted to smoke.

104
00:06:59,378 --> 00:07:00,294
Quit, dammit!

105
00:07:00,295 --> 00:07:03,005
You put so much work into this.

106
00:07:03,006 --> 00:07:04,590
He could've said forget it.

107
00:07:04,591 --> 00:07:08,386
- But he acts like it's his job at stake.
- It is!

108
00:07:08,387 --> 00:07:10,721
If you guys are fired,
who will I work with?

109
00:07:10,722 --> 00:07:11,974
Real sense of humanity.

110
00:07:12,933 --> 00:07:14,059
Damn.

111
00:07:16,436 --> 00:07:18,104
Stop!

112
00:07:18,105 --> 00:07:21,274
[man in English]
So, we're done with the tour here.

113
00:07:21,275 --> 00:07:23,986
Uh, we'll head back
to the headquarters in Seoul.

114
00:07:25,028 --> 00:07:26,321
Hello, sir.

115
00:07:26,947 --> 00:07:28,739
[in English] He wants to say something.

116
00:07:28,740 --> 00:07:29,824
[speaking Korean]

117
00:07:29,825 --> 00:07:34,245
[in English] In America, when you
get fired, you say, "You got axed."

118
00:07:34,246 --> 00:07:36,330
[in English]
Sorry, there's no other choice.

119
00:07:36,331 --> 00:07:37,540
[in English] Do you know
what we say in Korea?

120
00:07:37,541 --> 00:07:38,958
Off with your head!

121
00:07:38,959 --> 00:07:41,252
- So to be fired...
- Give back the helmet!

122
00:07:41,253 --> 00:07:43,588
...is to chop your head clear off!

123
00:07:43,589 --> 00:07:44,631
Wait!

124
00:07:45,883 --> 00:07:47,801
What'll he do with that helmet?

125
00:07:50,846 --> 00:07:51,972
[sighs]

126
00:07:54,892 --> 00:07:55,726
[man] They didn't...

127
00:07:56,685 --> 00:07:58,102
give you the eel, did they?

128
00:07:58,103 --> 00:08:00,105
[tense music playing]

129
00:08:02,941 --> 00:08:04,359
No way, right?

130
00:08:11,867 --> 00:08:13,201
Honey.

131
00:08:13,202 --> 00:08:14,368
[cicadas buzzing]

132
00:08:14,369 --> 00:08:15,953
What?

133
00:08:15,954 --> 00:08:17,080
You said you'd say something.

134
00:08:19,791 --> 00:08:21,125
I forgot.

135
00:08:21,126 --> 00:08:22,710
Aren't you going to work?

136
00:08:22,711 --> 00:08:23,836
Right, right.

137
00:08:23,837 --> 00:08:25,214
That's right.

138
00:08:26,798 --> 00:08:28,507
Si-two, Ri-two, house!

139
00:08:28,508 --> 00:08:31,178
Mmm. Study hard.

140
00:08:33,263 --> 00:08:35,389
- Ri-one, let's go.
- Ri-one!

141
00:08:35,390 --> 00:08:37,559
Have a good day.

142
00:08:40,896 --> 00:08:42,730
[engine starts]

143
00:08:42,731 --> 00:08:43,690
Good luck!

144
00:08:46,610 --> 00:08:48,946
I slaved for 25 years!

145
00:08:49,780 --> 00:08:51,031
[groans]

146
00:08:52,282 --> 00:08:53,325
[sighs]

147
00:08:57,037 --> 00:08:58,329
Deep breaths.

148
00:08:58,330 --> 00:09:06,171
[inhales then exhales]

149
00:09:07,256 --> 00:09:13,386
[inhales then exhales]

150
00:09:13,387 --> 00:09:14,929
[whimsical music playing]

151
00:09:14,930 --> 00:09:17,056
- [woman] I am...
- [men] I am...

152
00:09:17,057 --> 00:09:18,266
[woman] ...a good person.

153
00:09:18,267 --> 00:09:19,725
[all] ...a good person.

154
00:09:19,726 --> 00:09:20,851
[woman] Man-su!

155
00:09:20,852 --> 00:09:22,061
[Man-su] ...person.

156
00:09:22,062 --> 00:09:23,938
- [woman] Losing my job...
- [all] Losing my job...

157
00:09:23,939 --> 00:09:26,692
- [woman] Losing my job...
- [men] Losing my job...

158
00:09:27,359 --> 00:09:30,945
[woman] ...is not my choice!

159
00:09:30,946 --> 00:09:33,990
[men repeating]

160
00:09:33,991 --> 00:09:36,909
- [woman] My loving family...
- [men] My loving family...

161
00:09:36,910 --> 00:09:38,620
[woman] My loving family

162
00:09:39,496 --> 00:09:42,999
will support me fully
as I seek new opportunities.

163
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:47,962
...as I seek new opportunities.

164
00:09:47,963 --> 00:09:52,466
My loving family will support me fully

165
00:09:52,467 --> 00:09:55,804
as I seek new opportunities.

166
00:10:00,600 --> 00:10:02,185
[Miri over phone] Honey.

167
00:10:02,853 --> 00:10:04,353
Can you put in earphones?

168
00:10:04,354 --> 00:10:05,689
Just a sec.

169
00:10:07,190 --> 00:10:08,692
HIRED IN 3 MONTHS

170
00:10:10,902 --> 00:10:12,154
Uh...

171
00:10:12,738 --> 00:10:16,325
So you must've had
sleepless nights?

172
00:10:20,120 --> 00:10:21,330
Are you crying?

173
00:10:24,041 --> 00:10:28,879
Where's that brave bachelor
who proposed to a single mom?

174
00:10:29,463 --> 00:10:33,717
I made a new start, you can too.

175
00:10:34,551 --> 00:10:36,510
Sure you can!

176
00:10:36,511 --> 00:10:39,889
[woman] Take all your hopes and dreams,

177
00:10:39,890 --> 00:10:43,684
and recite your own incantation.

178
00:10:43,685 --> 00:10:44,894
Ready?

179
00:10:44,895 --> 00:10:46,520
Go!

180
00:10:46,521 --> 00:10:47,814
[men repeating]

181
00:10:48,815 --> 00:10:49,774
[Man-su] A new start.

182
00:10:49,775 --> 00:10:52,193
- [inaudible dialogue]
- A new start. A new start.

183
00:10:52,194 --> 00:10:54,696
A new start.

184
00:10:55,364 --> 00:10:56,948
I'm head of a family.

185
00:10:58,241 --> 00:10:59,659
I'll be born again.

186
00:11:00,869 --> 00:11:04,498
To put food in my family's mouths...

187
00:11:05,165 --> 00:11:06,792
there's nothing I won't do.

188
00:11:09,294 --> 00:11:10,712
In three months,

189
00:11:12,422 --> 00:11:14,174
I'll get hired again!

190
00:11:15,550 --> 00:11:16,426
[yells]

191
00:11:18,011 --> 00:11:19,679
I feel great!

192
00:11:20,847 --> 00:11:22,556
[groans softly]

193
00:11:22,557 --> 00:11:25,643
3 MONTHS LATER

194
00:11:25,644 --> 00:11:28,312
- 13 MONTHS LATER
- [cell phone chimes]

195
00:11:28,313 --> 00:11:30,398
Hi, Namgu, I know.

196
00:11:30,399 --> 00:11:31,565
Today at 5 o'clock.

197
00:11:31,566 --> 00:11:33,359
[Namgu] My boss is really
curious about you.

198
00:11:33,360 --> 00:11:34,276
[Man-su grunts]

199
00:11:34,277 --> 00:11:38,155
Sorry to ask so suddenly,
but can you come at noon?

200
00:11:38,156 --> 00:11:39,783
Listen, I'm...

201
00:11:40,700 --> 00:11:42,743
at the retail store, with my wife.

202
00:11:42,744 --> 00:11:44,161
[Namgu exclaims]

203
00:11:44,162 --> 00:11:48,332
The boss suddenly booked
a 5 p.m. flight back to China.

204
00:11:48,333 --> 00:11:51,001
- Too much to ask?
- No, no, hold on.

205
00:11:51,002 --> 00:11:54,755
Wait. I'll plead with my wife.

206
00:11:54,756 --> 00:11:58,175
[Namgu] That's right. Come over now.

207
00:11:58,176 --> 00:12:02,555
But there's a question he always asks.
"What's your weak point?"

208
00:12:02,556 --> 00:12:03,597
[Man-su] Weak point?

209
00:12:03,598 --> 00:12:08,185
[Namgu] It's a crucial-utely
sensitive issue, okay?

210
00:12:08,186 --> 00:12:09,729
[Man-su] Okay, thanks.

211
00:12:15,360 --> 00:12:17,445
[truck engine starts]

212
00:12:17,446 --> 00:12:19,823
[women laughing nearby]

213
00:12:22,868 --> 00:12:24,870
[truck engine revving]

214
00:12:27,205 --> 00:12:29,332
[indistinct chatter]

215
00:12:31,668 --> 00:12:32,793
[Miri] Weak point?

216
00:12:32,794 --> 00:12:35,880
[Man-su over phone] Sorry, I know it's
absolutely impossible to answer.

217
00:12:35,881 --> 00:12:37,631
What's my weak point?

218
00:12:37,632 --> 00:12:41,844
What do you think?
You love plants too much.

219
00:12:41,845 --> 00:12:43,388
You're a vegetable.

220
00:12:44,055 --> 00:12:46,056
Last night you called me an animal.

221
00:12:46,057 --> 00:12:47,309
[Miri chuckles mischievously]

222
00:12:48,393 --> 00:12:51,146
Namgu gave me this awesome tip.

223
00:12:52,647 --> 00:12:54,356
- MORTGAGE DEFAULT WARNING
- Oh.

224
00:12:54,357 --> 00:12:57,193
If only I can explain
my weak point well.

225
00:12:57,194 --> 00:13:00,613
- It's a crucial-utely sensitive issue.
- [dramatic music playing]

226
00:13:00,614 --> 00:13:05,659
If you're hired, you'll work
under your former subordinate, Namgu.

227
00:13:05,660 --> 00:13:07,953
Tell us how you feel about that.

228
00:13:07,954 --> 00:13:09,830
- I was a manager, true...
- [man translating in Mandarin]

229
00:13:09,831 --> 00:13:13,626
...but I've always considered
myself to be blue-collar.

230
00:13:13,627 --> 00:13:14,585
[shoe tapping]

231
00:13:14,586 --> 00:13:16,420
Hmm...

232
00:13:16,421 --> 00:13:18,506
So, in that respect...

233
00:13:18,507 --> 00:13:21,593
I don't think you understood the question.

234
00:13:22,886 --> 00:13:24,470
Namgu...

235
00:13:24,471 --> 00:13:27,640
No, of course I understand,
my point is...

236
00:13:27,641 --> 00:13:32,019
Namgu came to Papyrus first,
so you'll learn from him, right?

237
00:13:32,020 --> 00:13:34,063
- Of course!
- [translating in Mandarin]

238
00:13:34,064 --> 00:13:35,773
I am always learning.

239
00:13:35,774 --> 00:13:40,611
I got hired as soon as
I graduated from high school.

240
00:13:40,612 --> 00:13:45,157
But even while working,
I earned a chemistry degree.

241
00:13:45,158 --> 00:13:48,285
Of course, that was
at a distance university.

242
00:13:48,286 --> 00:13:49,746
Uh...

243
00:13:50,288 --> 00:13:51,580
Uh--

244
00:13:51,581 --> 00:13:56,502
Of course after that too,
I kept... learning.

245
00:13:56,503 --> 00:13:59,713
And of course, safety management.

246
00:13:59,714 --> 00:14:05,469
When I received the 2019
"Pulp Man of the Year,"

247
00:14:05,470 --> 00:14:10,724
it was that aspect
that they singled out in my record.

248
00:14:10,725 --> 00:14:13,561
And that same year,

249
00:14:13,562 --> 00:14:16,273
I finally bought my own home.

250
00:14:16,940 --> 00:14:20,192
The very house I was born in.

251
00:14:20,193 --> 00:14:21,611
Of course...

252
00:14:22,237 --> 00:14:24,613
I'm saying "of course" too much, aren't I?

253
00:14:24,614 --> 00:14:26,115
[chuckles]

254
00:14:26,116 --> 00:14:27,241
Uh...

255
00:14:27,242 --> 00:14:31,370
It's not so much because I'm nervous,

256
00:14:31,371 --> 00:14:35,958
but... self-confidence? Assurance?
That's what it is.

257
00:14:35,959 --> 00:14:37,252
Of course! [laughs]

258
00:14:38,461 --> 00:14:40,546
[laughing]

259
00:14:40,547 --> 00:14:42,131
[speaking Mandarin]

260
00:14:42,132 --> 00:14:46,761
[man translating] If you don't mind,
could you tell me about your weak point?

261
00:14:50,140 --> 00:14:51,558
No...

262
00:14:55,770 --> 00:14:57,605
[man translating in Mandarin]

263
00:14:57,606 --> 00:15:01,900
...is the one thing I can't say,
that's my biggest weak point!

264
00:15:01,901 --> 00:15:03,193
[laughing]

265
00:15:03,194 --> 00:15:05,780
[man translating in Mandarin]
Ha-ha-ha.

266
00:15:07,782 --> 00:15:09,908
Have you looked into Moon Paper?

267
00:15:09,909 --> 00:15:10,910
Moon?

268
00:15:11,536 --> 00:15:17,041
They say Moon Paper has cracked
the Japanese market, look into it.

269
00:15:17,042 --> 00:15:19,628
Pacific Paper is restructuring
this winter, too.

270
00:15:20,211 --> 00:15:21,129
Really?

271
00:15:21,921 --> 00:15:23,131
Go to a dentist, will you?

272
00:15:24,341 --> 00:15:26,800
Just go, okay? Huh?

273
00:15:26,801 --> 00:15:29,178
If you get hired,
you'll be too busy to go.

274
00:15:29,179 --> 00:15:30,596
No, I'm fine.

275
00:15:30,597 --> 00:15:33,350
There's that pigheadedness of yours!

276
00:15:34,100 --> 00:15:38,103
- Anyway, get hired before winter, okay?
- [man whispering indistinctly]

277
00:15:38,104 --> 00:15:40,065
The company will call you soon.

278
00:15:40,982 --> 00:15:43,984
- Thanks.
- [continues whispering]

279
00:15:43,985 --> 00:15:45,945
Don't forget, Moon Paper!

280
00:15:47,572 --> 00:15:51,450
[man whispering]
I'm a man. I'm a good person.

281
00:15:51,451 --> 00:15:54,662
Founded by legendary paper man
Moon Changho,

282
00:15:54,663 --> 00:15:55,746
CHOI SUN-CHUL, LINE MANAGER AT MOON PAPER

283
00:15:55,747 --> 00:15:57,247
- Moon Paper is...
- Mr. Choi!

284
00:15:57,248 --> 00:15:58,165
Yes?

285
00:15:58,166 --> 00:16:01,752
We agreed to talk about
how paper is made.

286
00:16:01,753 --> 00:16:02,711
That's what I'm--

287
00:16:02,712 --> 00:16:04,631
Leave the promotion
to the company channel.

288
00:16:05,465 --> 00:16:06,965
[woman] 6 hours 17 minutes later...

289
00:16:06,966 --> 00:16:11,595
Many people think paper companies
mindlessly raze entire forests, right?

290
00:16:11,596 --> 00:16:12,930
That's not true.

291
00:16:12,931 --> 00:16:14,933
[tense music playing]

292
00:16:22,732 --> 00:16:24,734
[owl hooting]

293
00:16:45,463 --> 00:16:48,090
[creaking]

294
00:16:48,091 --> 00:16:50,468
[grunts then mutters]

295
00:16:53,722 --> 00:16:54,723
[mouthing] What?

296
00:16:58,518 --> 00:17:00,477
[Miri] First, the good news.

297
00:17:00,478 --> 00:17:02,980
I got a part-time job.

298
00:17:02,981 --> 00:17:05,107
Mom's going out to work now.

299
00:17:05,108 --> 00:17:07,943
[Si-one] You always blamed us
for killing your career.

300
00:17:07,944 --> 00:17:10,237
Congrats, Mom.

301
00:17:10,238 --> 00:17:11,864
Thanks.

302
00:17:11,865 --> 00:17:14,283
Where? A dental clinic?

303
00:17:14,284 --> 00:17:17,870
- Dr. Oh Chin-ho.
- Dr. Ouch In-ho?

304
00:17:17,871 --> 00:17:19,538
No jokes allowed.

305
00:17:19,539 --> 00:17:23,375
I'd like us all to face the fact
we're in a crisis.

306
00:17:23,376 --> 00:17:26,879
Refrain from the listed activities
until Dad finds work.

307
00:17:26,880 --> 00:17:30,758
Except for Ri-one's lessons,
anything nonessential must go.

308
00:17:30,759 --> 00:17:32,176
For example...

309
00:17:32,177 --> 00:17:33,677
For example, meat in the soup?

310
00:17:33,678 --> 00:17:36,181
There is some, look harder.

311
00:17:38,725 --> 00:17:39,933
For example,

312
00:17:39,934 --> 00:17:41,352
my car.

313
00:17:42,145 --> 00:17:44,230
We'll trade your car
for something smaller.

314
00:17:47,275 --> 00:17:49,526
And our house.

315
00:17:49,527 --> 00:17:52,070
[tense music playing]

316
00:17:52,071 --> 00:17:53,155
Huh?

317
00:17:53,156 --> 00:17:54,615
- Huh?
- Huh?

318
00:17:54,616 --> 00:17:58,536
If we sell the house, we can pay off
our loans and rent an apartment.

319
00:18:01,873 --> 00:18:04,541
- You said you'd find work in three months.
- [groans softly]

320
00:18:04,542 --> 00:18:09,087
So we kept living as usual,
dipping into your severance pay.

321
00:18:09,088 --> 00:18:11,466
Now that's run dry.

322
00:18:17,680 --> 00:18:20,474
HOUSE FORECLOSURE IN 3 MONTHS

323
00:18:20,475 --> 00:18:21,643
[Man-su] Honey.

324
00:18:23,144 --> 00:18:24,521
This house...

325
00:18:25,647 --> 00:18:27,190
Ah...

326
00:18:28,566 --> 00:18:31,194
I have so many childhood memories
in this home.

327
00:18:32,529 --> 00:18:37,241
After turning 9, I moved
every 10 months on average.

328
00:18:37,242 --> 00:18:39,410
I worked so hard to buy back this home.

329
00:18:40,578 --> 00:18:41,788
- I mean, we did.
- [Miri sighs]

330
00:18:43,289 --> 00:18:44,414
With my own hands,

331
00:18:44,415 --> 00:18:46,750
I tore down the old barn,
built the greenhouse

332
00:18:46,751 --> 00:18:48,461
and the swing.

333
00:18:49,087 --> 00:18:51,129
Every corner of this home...

334
00:18:51,130 --> 00:18:52,131
Honey.

335
00:18:53,675 --> 00:18:56,469
If we go bankrupt, they'll take it anyway.

336
00:18:57,720 --> 00:18:59,137
The piano,

337
00:18:59,138 --> 00:19:01,181
living room table, two chairs,

338
00:19:01,182 --> 00:19:03,600
TV, curtain, carpet,

339
00:19:03,601 --> 00:19:05,143
have all been put up for sale.

340
00:19:05,144 --> 00:19:07,354
My racket, too. No more tennis.

341
00:19:07,355 --> 00:19:08,523
Let's quit dance lessons, too.

342
00:19:09,107 --> 00:19:10,774
Your bonsai magazine.

343
00:19:10,775 --> 00:19:13,068
And I'm canceling Netflix.

344
00:19:13,069 --> 00:19:14,362
[Si-one groans]

345
00:19:17,574 --> 00:19:18,408
Hey!

346
00:19:19,284 --> 00:19:21,953
Before it's canceled,
I should watch one more show.

347
00:19:23,913 --> 00:19:25,873
[Netflix's "ta-dum" sound logo plays]

348
00:19:25,874 --> 00:19:30,127
So comrades, now for the bad news.

349
00:19:30,128 --> 00:19:32,714
Something even worse?

350
00:19:37,218 --> 00:19:41,180
In these circumstances,
we can't afford to feed so many mouths.

351
00:19:43,099 --> 00:19:45,225
What do you mean, so many?

352
00:19:45,226 --> 00:19:47,645
- [Ri-one] Don't go, Ri-two.
- [Man-su] Ri-one.

353
00:19:48,396 --> 00:19:51,481
- [Miri] Si-one.
- We'll see them soon, okay, Ri-one?

354
00:19:51,482 --> 00:19:53,317
- [woman] Come on.
- [Ri-one whimpering]

355
00:19:53,318 --> 00:19:56,862
You can come visit them
at our house. Okay?

356
00:19:56,863 --> 00:20:00,198
Si-two, Ri-two will be back.
As soon as Dad gets hired.

357
00:20:00,199 --> 00:20:01,034
[dogs whining]

358
00:20:07,040 --> 00:20:09,208
[sneezes]

359
00:20:12,253 --> 00:20:13,837
That dog hair is brutal.

360
00:20:13,838 --> 00:20:15,840
[Miri] I'm sorry, Dad.

361
00:20:16,382 --> 00:20:17,674
Ah. [sniffles]

362
00:20:17,675 --> 00:20:19,552
- [Ri-one sobbing]
- [Man-su] Have a safe drive.

363
00:20:21,304 --> 00:20:23,097
[Miri] Let's go in. Come on.

364
00:20:24,599 --> 00:20:26,184
I'll bring them back soon, I will.

365
00:20:30,104 --> 00:20:31,314
[horn honking]

366
00:20:33,232 --> 00:20:34,733
Hello, ma'am!

367
00:20:34,734 --> 00:20:36,235
You're here early!

368
00:20:38,154 --> 00:20:40,573
The potential buyer is that dickhead?

369
00:20:41,658 --> 00:20:46,078
Oh. Not bad for a 50-year-old house.

370
00:20:46,079 --> 00:20:47,497
[agent] Look at the curtains.

371
00:20:48,039 --> 00:20:52,042
They fixed up this ruined house so well.

372
00:20:52,043 --> 00:20:53,710
It's been born again.

373
00:20:53,711 --> 00:20:56,797
- You know my townhouse near here?
- Yes.

374
00:20:56,798 --> 00:21:00,092
That land was originally
part of his dad's pig farm.

375
00:21:00,093 --> 00:21:03,053
Wow, if he still owned that land...

376
00:21:03,054 --> 00:21:06,932
If we tear down that greenhouse,
it'd make a great practice green.

377
00:21:06,933 --> 00:21:08,393
Oh.

378
00:21:09,435 --> 00:21:11,478
[whispering] Disgusting pig.

379
00:21:11,479 --> 00:21:14,898
[Wonno] You're quite the handyman,
You Man-su.

380
00:21:14,899 --> 00:21:16,525
Ooh.

381
00:21:16,526 --> 00:21:19,319
[plays off-key]

382
00:21:19,320 --> 00:21:21,072
That's enough for today.

383
00:21:22,490 --> 00:21:24,074
The moms are besties.

384
00:21:24,075 --> 00:21:25,994
The kids are besties.

385
00:21:28,162 --> 00:21:30,540
Ooh. Pulp Man of the Year!

386
00:21:32,250 --> 00:21:34,502
Your dad's gun is still looking good.

387
00:21:35,628 --> 00:21:37,462
VIETNAM WAR SERVICE CERTIFICATE

388
00:21:37,463 --> 00:21:39,465
[footsteps approaching]

389
00:21:41,009 --> 00:21:43,218
[agent] Oh, look here!

390
00:21:43,219 --> 00:21:49,349
Imagine waking up and seeing
that sturdy red pine!

391
00:21:49,350 --> 00:21:50,435
[Man-su] It's a white pine.

392
00:21:51,394 --> 00:21:52,644
White pine.

393
00:21:52,645 --> 00:21:55,272
Look around.
I'll stop by the dry cleaners.

394
00:21:55,273 --> 00:21:57,357
Pick up my clothes for an interview.

395
00:21:57,358 --> 00:21:59,902
[Wonno] You're a Man! Su! Fight!

396
00:22:01,821 --> 00:22:03,322
[agent] Shall we see the kids' rooms?

397
00:22:05,199 --> 00:22:07,659
[woman] With just one kid,
we'll use that as a closet.

398
00:22:07,660 --> 00:22:09,746
[agent] I thought that too.

399
00:22:11,414 --> 00:22:13,166
Nice mattress.

400
00:22:14,709 --> 00:22:16,836
That's for sale too. Buy it.

401
00:22:21,090 --> 00:22:22,592
[Dongho] Where will you move to?

402
00:22:23,926 --> 00:22:25,511
[Si-one] Need to sell the house first.

403
00:22:26,763 --> 00:22:28,264
[Dongho] Hope you don't go far.

404
00:22:30,308 --> 00:22:33,560
If we leave, Si-two, Ri-two
won't be able to find us.

405
00:22:33,561 --> 00:22:34,604
Says who?

406
00:22:44,572 --> 00:22:46,032
We're not leaving.

407
00:22:47,075 --> 00:22:48,284
I promise.

408
00:22:49,118 --> 00:22:52,496
Si-one, Ri-one, Si-one, Ri-one...

409
00:22:52,497 --> 00:22:54,498
Si-two, Ri-two, Si-two...

410
00:22:54,499 --> 00:22:56,333
- [man 1] Let me through!
- [grunting]

411
00:22:56,334 --> 00:22:58,795
- I'm late for a meeting.
- Listen, please.

412
00:22:59,712 --> 00:23:02,506
My wife is doing part-time work,

413
00:23:02,507 --> 00:23:05,133
we put our home up for sale,

414
00:23:05,134 --> 00:23:06,928
- canceled Netflix...
- What?

415
00:23:08,054 --> 00:23:09,888
- [man 2] Sir?
- Choi Sun-chul!

416
00:23:09,889 --> 00:23:12,307
What's going on? Who's this?

417
00:23:12,308 --> 00:23:14,059
He was fired from Solar.

418
00:23:14,060 --> 00:23:15,561
Just a sec.

419
00:23:17,897 --> 00:23:18,815
Come out.

420
00:23:20,691 --> 00:23:22,234
I'm sorry.

421
00:23:22,235 --> 00:23:24,778
[Sun-chul] Going to the meeting?
I wanted to talk to you.

422
00:23:24,779 --> 00:23:25,905
[man] Sure, then.

423
00:23:28,866 --> 00:23:29,700
Oh.

424
00:23:32,662 --> 00:23:34,913
Let me look...

425
00:23:34,914 --> 00:23:36,874
God, you're strong.

426
00:23:37,792 --> 00:23:38,835
[Man-su grunts]

427
00:23:41,212 --> 00:23:43,297
If you have any shame,

428
00:23:43,965 --> 00:23:47,009
don't do this in a place
where people shit and piss.

429
00:23:50,513 --> 00:23:51,639
Sir!

430
00:23:52,223 --> 00:23:55,600
I told you to come visit me!
We'll have a nice barbecue.

431
00:23:55,601 --> 00:23:57,562
All right, then.

432
00:24:08,906 --> 00:24:09,824
Oh, my.

433
00:24:12,076 --> 00:24:14,245
[scoffs] Listen.

434
00:24:15,204 --> 00:24:20,208
On the hill opposite, there's a nice
whiskey bar called Moon Shine.

435
00:24:20,209 --> 00:24:22,794
Have a drink on your way.

436
00:24:22,795 --> 00:24:26,381
I just moved here to Hoi Island.

437
00:24:26,382 --> 00:24:28,383
It's really gorgeous.

438
00:24:28,384 --> 00:24:32,388
Revealed for the first time ever!
Give a shout!

439
00:24:33,014 --> 00:24:37,350
Barbecue over my own wood fire
is out of this world!

440
00:24:37,351 --> 00:24:38,560
[grunts]

441
00:24:38,561 --> 00:24:40,313
Die!

442
00:24:41,480 --> 00:24:42,815
[exclaims]

443
00:24:43,816 --> 00:24:45,109
A-ha.

444
00:24:46,110 --> 00:24:47,319
[grunts]

445
00:24:47,320 --> 00:24:49,322
[smooth jazz music playing]

446
00:24:51,741 --> 00:24:54,159
[Sun-chul hisses]

447
00:24:54,160 --> 00:24:56,870
For each drop of sweat, a drop of whiskey.

448
00:24:56,871 --> 00:25:00,373
[Sun-chul] ♪ It's what I live for ♪

449
00:25:00,374 --> 00:25:03,460
- [buzzing]
- MS. WIFE

450
00:25:03,461 --> 00:25:04,502
Hi, honey.

451
00:25:04,503 --> 00:25:07,632
Listen, the cello teacher called--

452
00:25:08,216 --> 00:25:10,259
- Where are you?
- Huh?

453
00:25:11,969 --> 00:25:13,721
- Are you in a bar?
- No, no.

454
00:25:14,388 --> 00:25:16,432
Well, it's true.

455
00:25:17,225 --> 00:25:18,350
It's true, but I'm not.

456
00:25:18,351 --> 00:25:19,352
Look.

457
00:25:21,062 --> 00:25:22,187
I'm by myself.

458
00:25:22,188 --> 00:25:23,189
Have you gone mad?

459
00:25:23,940 --> 00:25:26,358
- I'm drinking this, really.
- Whiskey?

460
00:25:26,359 --> 00:25:27,984
This here.

461
00:25:27,985 --> 00:25:31,279
[sighs] You went to a bar
to drink apple juice?

462
00:25:31,280 --> 00:25:34,617
Honey, you trust me?

463
00:25:36,911 --> 00:25:38,787
Of course.

464
00:25:38,788 --> 00:25:40,330
Why'd the cello teacher call?

465
00:25:40,331 --> 00:25:46,170
- I can't teach Ri-one anymore.
- [playing slow-tempo tune on cello]

466
00:25:47,421 --> 00:25:48,463
What?

467
00:25:48,464 --> 00:25:51,549
Ri-one's talent is too...

468
00:25:51,550 --> 00:25:53,552
outstanding? [chuckles nervously]

469
00:25:54,136 --> 00:25:55,096
[chuckles]

470
00:25:58,391 --> 00:25:59,934
But ma'am,

471
00:26:01,269 --> 00:26:04,897
how can I believe you?

472
00:26:05,606 --> 00:26:09,735
She doesn't play for us.

473
00:26:10,778 --> 00:26:14,406
We've never heard anything
but a few notes.

474
00:26:14,407 --> 00:26:15,365
Right.

475
00:26:15,366 --> 00:26:21,246
Why do you think I'd give up
my lesson fee to another teacher?

476
00:26:21,247 --> 00:26:23,039
Another teacher?

477
00:26:23,040 --> 00:26:25,960
Ri-one needs to learn
from a music professor now.

478
00:26:27,878 --> 00:26:31,715
But you should know,
the fee is on a different level than mine.

479
00:26:31,716 --> 00:26:32,591
Ah.

480
00:26:34,677 --> 00:26:35,635
[chuckles nervously]

481
00:26:35,636 --> 00:26:41,892
You said you wanted Ri-one
to be able to live independently.

482
00:26:45,271 --> 00:26:47,731
If so, this level of investment...

483
00:26:47,732 --> 00:26:50,484
- [inaudible cello music]
- [Sun-chul on video] I'll say two things.

484
00:26:51,402 --> 00:26:55,405
Many people think paper companies
mindlessly raze entire forests, right?

485
00:26:55,406 --> 00:26:57,407
- That's not true.
- [cello music playing over headphones]

486
00:26:57,408 --> 00:27:01,119
Trees for paper are grown separately, cut,

487
00:27:01,120 --> 00:27:03,872
planted again, grown and cut again.

488
00:27:03,873 --> 00:27:04,914
[woman on video] Ah.

489
00:27:04,915 --> 00:27:07,959
[Sun-chul] And that's not all.
There's reuse.

490
00:27:07,960 --> 00:27:10,253
We collect waste paper, recycle it...

491
00:27:10,254 --> 00:27:11,463
[woman] Oh.

492
00:27:11,464 --> 00:27:14,967
- ...then collect it again and--
- [Miri] What are you watching?

493
00:27:17,803 --> 00:27:20,889
The only company doing well
these days is Moon Paper.

494
00:27:20,890 --> 00:27:24,392
They cracked the Japanese market.
He's line manager of specialty paper.

495
00:27:24,393 --> 00:27:25,435
[cello music continues]

496
00:27:25,436 --> 00:27:27,980
A perfect job for you.
You're good at Japanese, too.

497
00:27:29,774 --> 00:27:33,777
[Sun-chul on video] Korea's the most
advanced country in paper reuse.

498
00:27:33,778 --> 00:27:35,403
- [woman] Ah.
- [Sun-chul laughs]

499
00:27:35,404 --> 00:27:37,489
Unlimited reuse!

500
00:27:37,490 --> 00:27:39,324
Freaking unlimited reuse!

501
00:27:39,325 --> 00:27:41,534
Compared to my husband, he's nothing.

502
00:27:41,535 --> 00:27:43,537
[Sun-chul continues speaking indistinctly]

503
00:27:44,330 --> 00:27:46,915
- Can't he get hit by lightning?
- [chuckles]

504
00:27:46,916 --> 00:27:51,836
Pointy umbrella in a thunderstorm.
[chuckling]

505
00:27:51,837 --> 00:27:53,839
[tense music playing]

506
00:27:55,674 --> 00:27:57,759
[men laughing]

507
00:27:57,760 --> 00:27:59,762
[soft suspenseful music playing]

508
00:28:04,809 --> 00:28:07,269
CHOI SUN-CHUL

509
00:28:42,388 --> 00:28:44,890
Sure, it's fabulous!

510
00:28:46,434 --> 00:28:48,853
Try living there just one week.

511
00:28:51,772 --> 00:28:54,567
An apartment can't even compare!

512
00:28:57,361 --> 00:28:58,778
[Man-su muttering]

513
00:28:58,779 --> 00:29:01,906
[Sun-chul]
Come on, the ferry runs so often!

514
00:29:01,907 --> 00:29:04,033
[Man-su continues muttering]

515
00:29:04,034 --> 00:29:05,910
[Sun-chul] I'm telling you.

516
00:29:05,911 --> 00:29:10,248
I know that, but it's so quiet there.

517
00:29:10,249 --> 00:29:12,334
Air's clean, it's fabulous.

518
00:29:14,128 --> 00:29:15,463
Even more fabulous at night.

519
00:29:20,009 --> 00:29:22,011
[barking]

520
00:29:29,727 --> 00:29:30,644
[Sun-chul] Right.

521
00:29:33,481 --> 00:29:35,774
No, there aren't any!

522
00:29:36,484 --> 00:29:40,821
If you're scared, we'll raise chickens.
They eat snakes.

523
00:29:41,864 --> 00:29:43,406
What?

524
